TY  - JOUR
AU  - Heston, Steven L.
AU  - Loewenstein, Mark
AU  - Willard, Gregory A.
T1  - Options and Bubbles
PY  - 2007
Y1  - 2007/03/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhl005
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 20
IS  - 2
SP  - 359
EP  - 390
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - The Black-Scholes-Merton option valuation method involves deriving and solving a partial differential equation (PDE). But this method can generate multiple values for an option. We provide new solutions for the Cox-Ingersoll-Ross (CIR) term structure model, the constant elasticity of variance (CEV) model, and the Heston stochastic volatility model. Multiple solutions reflect asset pricing bubbles, dominated investments, and (possibly infeasible) arbitrages. We provide conditions to rule out bubbles on underlying prices. If they are not satisfied, put-call parity might not hold, American calls have no optimal exercise policy, and lookback calls have infinite value. We clarify a longstanding conjecture of Cox, Ingersoll, and Ross. (JEL G12 and G13)
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhl005
ER  - 



